The paper discusses the use of non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) in massive multi-in multi-out (MIMO) systems, which involves the use of multiple antennas at both the base station and user devices. This topic falls under the intersection of several computer science sub-disciplines, including information theory (cs.IT), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), systems and control (cs.SY), multimedia (cs.MM), and computer communication (cs.COM). Given the focus on wireless communication and signal processing, cs.IT and cs.NI are the most likely categories. The discussion of beamforming and hybrid schemes also suggests cs.SY and cs.COM as possible categories. Finally, the use of massive MIMO and the comparison of different access schemes may also fall under cs.MM.
